description: If you took Tylenol during your pregnancy and your child is autistic, I am here to lovingly remove any guilt you may feel that you somehow caused this. You did not. People with Austism are valued members of our society. In 2013, the criteria for someone to be diagnosed as autistic was expanded which exploded the cases being ‚Äúfound‚Äù. Because we were LOOKING. We only thought there were so many stars in the sky until we updated our technology to find more. When you‚Äôre using a telescope, you see more stars. It doesn‚Äôt mean they weren‚Äôt there before. Please talk to your trusted health care provider to get accurate medical information to help guide your medical decisions. title: DANG‚ÄîI‚Äôve seen at least 5 of these in the past couple weeks
description: DANG‚ÄîI‚Äôve seen at least 5 of these in the past couple weeks. What is going on?! Every choice in labor has ‚ú®nuance‚ú® A few ones I‚Äôve seen recently‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúNever consent to cervical exams‚Äù‚Äîthe more cervical exams you have, the higher your risk of infection. They can also be a helpful piece of information if you‚Äôre debating a decision (deciding to get an epidural or augmenting your labor), being induced, or they can help us find out what is going on if your baby shows us they are in trouble on the monitor. ‚ÄúNever consent to a vacuum or forceps‚Äù‚Äîthese choices are never (üòú I said never) brought up when things are going awesome. They are done for two reasons. Fetal distress or maternal exhaustion. So basically if you just can‚Äôt push anymore and ask for help OR your baby is showing signs of severe stress and waiting would cause damage to your baby‚Äôs brain. If these are brought up, the recommendation is either vacuum, forceps, or c-section. ‚ÄúNever consent to an episiotomy‚Äù‚Äîdoing an episiotomy for fun is not cool. But it is also a life-saving/brain-saving intervention used during emergencies like a terminal bradycardia or a shoulder dystocia to help get your baby here safely. ‚ÄúNever let them break your water‚Äù‚Äîthe longer your water is broken, the higher chance of infection. It also carries risks like cord prolapse or fetal distress. But you may also choose to have your water broken in other scenarios like being 8cm without an epidural for a few hours when you are exhausted and just want to be done. ‚ÄúNever have an elective induction‚Äù‚Äîbeing induced when your body isn‚Äôt ready can be a long, painful process that can also lead to a c-section. But you may choose to be induced for whatever reason makes sense to you. Bottom line‚Äîevery intervention is a tool. We should never throw our entire toolbox at someone. We should carefully consider every choice. Your provider should be giving you all your choices, all the risks, benefits, and alternatives. And YOU get to be the one to decide what makes sense for you. I will support every informed and empowered decision you make. Even if I wouldn‚Äôt do the same.

title: ‚ÄúPreeclampsia (pre-e-CLAMP-si-a) is persistent high blood pressure that develops during pregnancy or
description: ‚ÄúPreeclampsia (pre-e-CLAMP-si-a) is persistent high blood pressure that develops during pregnancy or the postpartum period. It is often associated with high levels of protein in the urine or the new development of decreased blood platelets, trouble with the kidneys or liver, fluid in the lungs, or signs of brain trouble such as seizures and/or visual disturbances. Preeclampsia is diagnosed by the elevation of the expectant patient's blood pressure usually after the 20th week of pregnancy and is unique to human pregnancy. According to guidelines released by the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, the diagnosis of preeclampsia no longer requires the detection of high levels of protein in the urine (proteinuria). Evidence shows that problems with the kidneys and liver can occur without signs of protein in the urine. The amount of protein in the urine does not predict how severely the disease will progress. Most healthcare providers traditionally adhered to a rigid diagnosis of preeclampsia based on blood pressure and protein in the urine prior to these new guidelines. Preeclampsia is now diagnosed by persistent high blood pressure that develops during pregnancy or the postpartum period that is associated with high levels of protein in the urine OR the new development of decreased blood platelets, trouble with the kidneys or liver, fluid in the lungs, or signs of brain trouble such as seizures and/or visual disturbances. Important symptoms that may suggest preeclampsia are headaches, abdominal pain, shortness of breath or burning behind the sternum, nausea and vomiting, confusion, heightened state of anxiety, and/or visual disturbances such as oversensitivity to light, blurred vision, or seeing flashing spots or auras. Preeclampsia and related hypertensive disorders of pregnancy impact 5-8% of all births in the United States. Most women with preeclampsia will deliver healthy babies and fully recover. However, some women will experience complications, several of which may be life-threatening to mother and/or baby. A woman‚Äôs condition can progress to severe preeclampsia very quickly. The rate of preeclampsia in the US has increased 25% in the last two decades and is a leading cause of maternal and infant illness and death. Preeclampsia and other hypertensive disorders of pregnancy can be devastating diseases, made worse by delays in diagnosis or management, seriously impacting or even killing both women and their babies before, during or after birth.‚Äù -The Pre-Eclampsia Foundation

title: Three years ago, I saw an anonymous post in a mom‚Äôs group on FB asking for help with cleaning
description: Three years ago, I saw an anonymous post in a mom‚Äôs group on FB asking for help with cleaning company recommendations. This mom was suffering from postpartum depression and was paralyzed with the overwhelm she was feeling. She mentioned that she really couldn‚Äôt afford a cleaner but was desperate. I thought‚Äîthis is a mom‚Äôs group. We are the villiage. Why can‚Äôt we rescue this girl? I made a separate post asking if anyone would be willing to go with me to her house and do all the things that are too hard to do when life gets tough. Just a couple of days later, about 10 complete strangers met up at a McDonald‚Äôs to carpool to her house. We showed up with brooms/mops/paper towels and trash bags and spent all day making sure we left her with a more peaceful existence. I didn‚Äôt know it then, but that was our very first Hot Mess Express mission. Three years later and we are now a national nonprofit with thousands of members. To join our mission or to start a group in your area, head to hotmessexpress.co

title: Pitocin is the most used medication on a labor floor
description: Pitocin is the most used medication on a labor floor. When used appropriately and with caution, it can hasten birth when it needs to be hastened or help stop a hemorrhage after a baby is born. But it also can be the start of a cascade of interventions that can lead to us ‚Äúsaving the day‚Äù due to something that we caused. I am a firm believer that spontaneous labor happens just as it should in MOST cases. Using Pitocin during labor should be the exception and not a standard thing that everyone gets just ‚Äúbecause‚Äù. We need to be giving people truly informed consent for EVERY INTERVENTION and giving EVERY PATIENT truly individualized care. Pitocin is like fire. When used appropriately and in the right contexts, it can be used as a tool‚Äîyou can cook with it, you can get warm. But when you start a fire inappropriately or carelessly, you can cause harm. Talk to your own trusted health care team about risks/benefits/options for your care. ‚ù§Ô∏è I got Pitocin with both of my labors so I‚Äôm not anti-Pitocin. But I am PRO-INFORMED CONSENT AND INDIVIDUALIZED CARE.
